1 (i) The operation of electronic devices whose sound cannot be muted is
2 prohibited on the floor or in the gallery while the Senate is in session.
3 (j) No member of the Senate shall place any item on another Senator's Chamber
4 desk or in another Senator's office unless the item conspicuously displays the name of the Senator
5 placing the item.
6 (k) No person other than the member, the member's legislative assistant, or the
7 Principal Clerk's office or staff under the direction of the Principal Clerk shall place any matter
8 on the member's Chamber desk, then only materials relevant to the business of the Senate, or as
9 allowed under subsection (j) of this rule.
10 (l) Neither food nor beverage shall be permitted in the galleries.
11 III. MOTIONS
12 RULE 18. Motions generally. – Any motion shall be reduced to writing, if requested
13 by the Presiding Officer or a Senator, and read by the Presiding Officer or Reading Clerk before
14 the same is debated. Any motion may be withdrawn by the introducer at any time before decision
15 or amendment. No motion relating to a bill shall be in order which does not identify the bill by
16 its number and short title. Except as otherwise specifically provided in these rules, no second is
17 required.
18 RULE 19. Motion; order of precedence. – When a question is before the Senate, no
19 motion shall be received except those herein specified, which motions shall have precedence as
20 follows:
21 (1) To adjourn.
22 (2) To resolve into the Committee of the Whole Senate.
23 (3) To lay on the table.
24 (4) For the previous question.
25 (5) To postpone indefinitely.
26 (6) To postpone to a certain day.
27 (7) To re-refer to a standing committee.
28 (8) To refer to a select committee.
29 (9) To amend.
30 RULE 20. Motions requiring a second. – The motions to adjourn, to resolve into the
31 Committee of the Whole Senate, to lay on the table, and to call for the previous question shall be
32 seconded and decided without debate.
33 RULE 21. Motions to postpone to certain day and to commit. – The respective
34 motions to postpone to a certain day, to resolve into the Committee of the Whole Senate, or to
35 commit to a standing or select committee shall preclude debate on the main question.
36 RULE 22. Motion to substitute. – Subject to Rule 19, a member may offer a motion
37 to substitute to any motion, except the motions for the previous question, to table, to resolve into
38 the Committee of the Whole Senate, or to adjourn. No motion to substitute shall be offered to a
39 motion to substitute.
40 RULE 23. Motion for previous question. – (a) The previous question may be moved
41 upon a pending single motion, any pending amendment or amendments, and/or the pending bill
42 to its passage on that reading or all readings or the pending resolution to its adoption. An
43 authorized Senator moving the previous question shall specify to what the motion applies. Unless
44 specified, the motion shall be deemed to apply to the current question.
45 (b) The previous question shall be as follows: "Shall the main question be now
46 put?" and until it is decided shall preclude all amendments and debate. If this question is decided
47 in the affirmative, the "main question" shall be on the passage of the bill, resolution, or other
48 matter under consideration; but when amendments are pending, the question shall be taken upon
49 such amendments in their inverse order, without further debate or amendment.
50 (c) Only one of the following Senators may move the previous question:
Senate Resolution 1-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The chair of the committee submitting the report on the bill or other matter
2 under consideration;
3 (2) The member introducing the bill or other matter under consideration;
4 (3) The member in charge of the measure, who shall be designated by the chair
5 of the committee reporting the same to the Senate at the time the bill or other
6 matter under consideration is reported to the Senate or taken up for
7 consideration;
8 (4) The Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate; or
9 (5) The President Pro Tempore.
10 RULE 24. Motion to reconsider. – (a) When a question has been once put and
11 decided, any Senator who voted in the majority may move to reconsider the vote thereof. No
12 motion for reconsideration shall be in order unless made on the same day or on the next legislative
13 day on which the vote took place. When the next legislative day has by motion of the Senate been
14 restricted as to matters which may be considered, a motion to reconsider shall be in order on the
15 next succeeding day upon which regular business is conducted. No question shall be reconsidered
16 more than once.
17 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this rule, a motion to reconsider is in order
18 at any time if made by the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate or the
19 President Pro Tempore for the sole purpose of correcting grammatical errors in bills in the
20 possession of the Senate.
21 (c) If a bill has gone out of the possession of the Senate and a motion to reconsider
22 under these rules is passed, the bill shall not be enrolled unless it again passes third reading. The
23 Principal Clerk shall notify the House of Representatives and the Enrolling Clerk of any action
24 under this subsection.
25 RULE 24.1. Motion to adjourn; motion to stand in recess; standard stipulations.
26 – A motion to adjourn or stand in recess shall be subject to receipt and referral of committee
27 reports, the introduction of bills, referral and re-referral of bills, reading of Senatorial Statements,
28 receipt of House messages, ratification of bills, announcement of committee assignments, and
29 messages from the Governor.
30 A Senator may request that a motion to adjourn be made in honor or in memory of a
31 person or an event of significance. The request shall be in writing and shall be submitted to the
32 Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate on the day prior to the day the
33 motion to adjourn is to be made.
34 IV. VOTING
35 RULE 25. Use of electronic voting system. – (a) Votes on the following questions
36 shall be taken on the electronic voting system, and the ayes and noes shall be recorded on the
37 Journal:
38 (1) All questions on which the Constitution of North Carolina requires that the
39 ayes and noes be taken and recorded on the Journal;
40 (2) All questions on which a call for the ayes and noes under Rule 26(b) has been
41 sustained;
42 (3) Second and third readings of bills proposing amendment of the Constitution
43 of North Carolina; and
44 (4) The vote on approval of a bill that was vetoed by the Governor.
45 (b) Votes on the following questions shall be taken on the electronic voting
46 system, and the resulting totals shall be recorded on the Journal:
47 (1) Second reading of all public bills, all amendments to public bills offered after
48 second reading, third reading if a public bill was amended after second
49 reading, and all conference reports on public bills.
50 (2) Any other question upon direction of the Presiding Officer or upon motion of
51 any Senator supported by one-fifth of the Senators present.
Page 6 Senate Resolution 1-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (c) When the electronic voting system is used, the Presiding Officer shall fix and
2 announce the time, not to exceed one minute, which shall be allowed for voting on the question
3 before the Senate. The system shall be set to lock automatically and to record the vote when that
4 time has expired. Once the system has locked and recorded a vote, the vote shall be printed by
5 the system.
6 (d) The voting station at each Senator's desk in the Chamber shall be used only
7 by the Senator to whom the station is assigned. Under no circumstances shall any other person
8 vote at a Senator's station. It is a breach of the ethical obligation of a Senator either to request
9 that another vote at the requesting Senator's station or to vote at another Senator's station. The
10 Presiding Officer shall enforce this rule without exception.
11 (e) When the electronic voting system is used, the Presiding Officer shall state
12 the question and shall then state substantially the following: "All in favor vote 'aye'; all opposed
13 vote 'no'; _____ seconds will be allowed for voting on this question; the Clerk will record the
14 vote." After the machine locks and records the vote, the Presiding Officer shall announce the
15 vote and declare the result, and no member may vote thereafter.
16 (f) One copy of the machine printout of the vote record shall be filed in the Office
17 of the Principal Clerk, and one copy shall be filed in the Legislative Library where it shall be
18 open to public inspection.
19 (g) When the Presiding Officer ascertains that the electronic voting system is
20 inoperative before a vote is taken or while a vote is being taken on the electronic system, the
21 Presiding Officer shall announce that fact to the Senate, and any partial electronic system voting
22 record shall be voided. In such a case, if the Constitution of North Carolina or the Rules of the
23 Senate require a call of the ayes and noes, the Clerk shall call the roll of the Senate, and the ayes
24 and noes shall be taken manually and shall be recorded on the Journal. All other votes shall be
25 taken as prescribed in Senate Rule 26. If, after a vote is taken on the electronic system, it is
26 discovered that a malfunction caused an error in the electronic system printout, the Presiding
27 Officer shall direct the Reading Clerk and the Principal Clerk to verify and correct the printout
28 record and so advise the Senate.
29 (h) For the purpose of identifying motions on which the vote is taken on the
30 electronic system (the identification codes having no relation to the order of precedence of
31 motions), the motions are coded as follows:
32 (1) To lay on the table.
33 (2) To resolve into the Committee of the Whole Senate.
34 (3) For the previous question.
35 (4) To postpone indefinitely.
36 (5) To postpone to a day certain.
37 (6) To refer to a committee.
38 (7) To reconsider.
39 (8) To adopt.
40 (9) To concur.
41 (10) To take from the table.
42 (11) Miscellaneous.
43 RULE 26. Voice votes; call for division; call for ayes and noes. – (a) When the
44 electronic voting system is not used, all votes on which a call of the roll of the Senate is not
45 required shall be taken by voice vote. The question shall be put as follows: "Those in favor say
46 'aye,'" and, after the affirmative vote is expressed, "Opposed 'no'"; after which the Presiding
47 Officer shall announce the result. If a division on any vote is desired, it must be called for
48 immediately before the result of the voting is announced on any question, and, upon such call,
49 the Presiding Officer shall require the members to stand and be counted for and against the
50 proposition under consideration.
