1 (b) The ayes and the noes may be called for on any question before the vote is
2 taken. If a Senator desires the ayes and noes recorded on the Journal on a question, that Senator
3 shall address the Presiding Officer and obtain recognition and say, "Upon that question I call for
4 the ayes and noes." Whereupon the Presiding Officer shall say, "Is the call sustained?" If one-fifth
5 of the remaining Senators present then stand, the vote shall be taken on the electronic voting
6 system if it is operative, and the ayes and noes shall be recorded on the Journal. If the electronic
7 voting system is inoperative, the roll of the Senate shall be called and the ayes and noes taken
8 manually and recorded on the Journal. If fewer than one-fifth of the Senators present stand to
9 sustain the call, the Presiding Officer shall announce, "An insufficient number up," and a vote by
10 electronic voting or by voice, whichever is appropriate under the Rules of the Senate, shall be
11 taken.
12 RULE 27. (Reserved for future use).
13 RULE 28. Dividing question. – (a) If a bill is subject to division into separate parts
14 so that each part states a separate and distinct proposition capable of standing alone, a Senator
15 may move that the question be divided. The motion shall:
16 (1) Be in writing,
17 (2) Be submitted to the Principal Clerk at the time the motion is made, and
18 (3) Clearly state how the question is to be divided.
19 Upon a majority vote of the membership of the Senate present and voting, the motion shall be
20 adopted.
21 (b) If the motion to divide the question is adopted, then there shall be no further
22 amendment or debate on any of the distinct propositions.
23 (c) If the question is divided and any part thereof fails, then the bill or resolution
24 and any pending amendments shall be removed from the calendar and re-referred to the
25 committee from which the bill or resolution was reported.
26 (d) Only one motion to divide the question shall be in order during consideration
27 of a bill or resolution.
28 RULE 29. Duty to vote; excuses. – (a) Every Senator who is within the Senate
29 Chamber when the question is stated by the Presiding Officer shall vote thereon unless that
30 Senator is excused by the Senate.
31 (b) A Senator who is a member of a committee shall, upon request, be excused
32 from deliberations and voting on the bill while it is before the committee. The Senator must make
33 the request to the chair of the committee when the bill is first taken up for consideration and
34 before any motion or vote on the bill or any amendment to the bill. The Senator making the
35 request for excuse in committee must renew that request for excuse on the floor of the Senate as
36 set forth in this rule.
37 (c) Any Senator may move to be excused at any time from voting on any matter.
38 The Senator may make a brief statement of the reasons for the motion which question shall be
39 taken without debate on the motion.
40 (d) The Senator may send forward to the Principal Clerk, on a form provided by
41 the Clerk, a concise statement of the reason for the motion, and the Clerk shall include this
42 statement in the Journal.
43 (e) The Senator so excused shall not debate the bill or any amendment to the bill,
44 vote on the bill, offer or vote on any amendment to the bill, or offer or vote on any motion
45 concerning the bill at that reading, any subsequent reading, or any subsequent consideration of
46 the bill.
47 (f) A Senator may move that the excuse of that Senator from deliberations on a
48 particular bill be withdrawn, which question shall be determined without debate. The Senator
49 shall send forward to the Principal Clerk, on a form provided by the Clerk, the written request.
50 (g) A motion to be excused or for the withdrawal of an excuse shall be taken
51 without debate.
