1 (b) The President Pro Tempore and the Deputy President Pro Tempore may serve
2 as voting ex officio members of each Senate committee and subcommittee.
3 (c) The Vice-Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate may
4 exercise any authority given to the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate
5 under these rules in the absence of, or at the direction of, the Chair.
6 RULE 35. Roll call vote in committee. – No roll call vote may be taken in any
7 committee. The committee chair may vote in committee.
8 RULE 36. Standing committee and standing subcommittee meetings. – No
9 committee or subcommittee shall hold a secret meeting. All meetings of committees and
10 subcommittees shall be open to the public, except as provided in G.S. 143-318.14A(e). In no
11 event shall final action be taken by any committee or subcommittee except in open session.
12 RULE 36.1. Committee minutes to Legislative Library. – The chair of a committee
13 shall ensure that minutes, in a format and medium approved by the Chair of the Committee on
14 Rules and Operations of the Senate, are compiled for each of the committee's meetings. The
15 minutes shall indicate the number of members present and the actions taken by the committee at
16 the meeting. Not later than 30 days after the adjournment of each session of the General
17 Assembly, the chair shall deliver the minutes to the Legislative Library. The President Pro
18 Tempore of the Senate may grant a reasonable extension of time for filing said minutes upon
19 application of the committee chair.
20 RULE 37. Committee of the Whole Senate. – Notwithstanding the provisions of
21 Rules 33, 34, and 35, the Senate may resolve into the Committee of the Whole Senate by motion.
22 When such a motion is seconded, the President shall put the question without debate: "Shall the
23 Senate resolve itself into the Committee of the Whole Senate for consideration of ________?'',
24 stating the matter or matters identified by the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations
25 of the Senate to be considered. Only the President Pro Tempore, the Deputy President Pro
26 Tempore, or the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate may move to
27 resolve into the Committee of the Whole Senate. The Committee of the Whole Senate shall
28 convene in the Senate Chambers and shall utilize electronic voting. Unless otherwise stated, the
29 Rules and Operations of the Senate apply to the Committee of the Whole Senate and the Principal
30 Clerk of the Senate shall be the Committee Assistant, but shall not record committee activity on
31 the Journal. The Chair shall be the President Pro Tempore of the Senate or his designee.
32 RULE 37.1. Membership, quorum, and voting. – Every Senator shall be a member
33 of the Committee of the Whole Senate. A quorum of a Committee of the Whole Senate is 26
34 members.
35 RULE 37.2. Committee substitutes; report of the Committee of the Whole
36 Senate; adjournment. – (a) The committee of the Whole Senate shall not consider committee
37 substitutes.
38 (b) The Chair may entertain a motion that the Committee adjourn after the Chair
39 has announced that the Committee has finished the business for which it was convened.
40 (c) The Chair of the Committee of the Whole Senate shall report the bill to the
41 Senate immediately following the adjournment of the Committee, including any amendments
42 that were adopted in the Committee.
43 (d) The Chair shall announce the adjournment of the Committee of the Whole
44 Senate and the members shall adjourn and, if the Committee was resolved out of an unadjourned
45 session, the Senate shall resume session.
46 VI. HANDLING BILLS
47 RULE 38. Application of rules. – All provisions of these rules applying to bills,
48 including, but not limited to, provisions governing the introduction, eligibility, and filing of bills,
49 shall apply also to resolutions and petitions.
50 RULE 39. Form of bills. – (a) Unless variation is authorized by the Committee on
51 Rules and Operations of the Senate, bills submitted for introduction shall be in a
Page 10 Senate Resolution 1-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 computer-generated form prepared by the Legislative Services Office and approved by the
2 Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate.
3 (b) Whenever a bill is filed, it shall be submitted to the Principal Clerk in the form
4 of a Senate e-jacket.
5 RULE 39.1. Public and local bills; limitation on local bills becoming public bills.
6 – (a) A public bill is a bill affecting 15 or more counties. A local bill is one affecting fewer than
7 15 counties. No bill may be considered unless the bill has been made available to the entire
8 membership of the Senate.
9 (b) A local bill that has become a public bill shall not be considered in the Senate
10 unless one of the following applies:
11 (1) The North Carolina Constitution prescribes that the bill as filed must be a
12 public bill because of its subject matter.
13 (2) The bill became a public bill because counties were added, but the bill relates
14 to the subject matter contained in the original bill.
15 RULE 40. Introduction of bills. – (a) Pursuant to G.S. 120-11.1, on January 8, 2025,
16 a simple resolution to establish the Senate Permanent Rules, and a joint resolution to adjourn to
17 January 29, 2025, may be filed. No other bills are eligible to be filed on January 8, 2025.
18 (a1) Every bill filed for introduction shall contain on the Senate e-jacket the title
19 of the document and the name of the Senator or Senators sponsoring it. No more than three
20 Senators may be listed as primary sponsors. The Senator whose name appears first shall deliver
21 the Senate e-jacket to the Office of the Principal Clerk either physically or electronically using
22 the member's electronic dashboard. Subject to any authorization prescribed by the Principal
23 Clerk, a member's legislative assistant may deliver a Senate e-jacket by any method allowed
24 under this rule.
25 (a2) The Senate Principal Clerk shall receive bills for introduction during regular
26 session on any day the Senate holds a session until 4:00 P.M.
27 (a3) All bills shall be numbered by the Office of the Principal Clerk when filed and
28 shall be considered introduced when presented to the Senate on the next legislative day for the
29 first reading. When a bill is presented with more than one primary sponsor, the Chair of the
30 Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate shall designate, as bill manager, one of the
31 primary sponsors. Senators may only cosponsor legislation electronically.
32 (b) Any Senator who wishes to cosponsor a bill or resolution that has been filed
33 may do so no later than 5:00 P.M. on the next legislative day after the adjournment of the session
34 during which the bill or resolution was first read and referred, but only electronically under
35 procedures approved by the Principal Clerk.
36 (c) No member may introduce a public bill that has no substantive provisions. A
37 member may introduce one local bill that contains no substantive provisions in an odd-numbered
38 year. A member may introduce one local bill that contains no substantive provisions in an
39 even-numbered year if the bill is otherwise eligible and either (i) the member did not introduce
40 such a bill during the previous year or (ii) the member did introduce such a bill during the
41 previous year but no substantive provisions were added.
42 RULE 40.1. Limitations on certain resolutions. – (a) A Senator may file a resolution
43 that memorializes, celebrates, commends, or commemorates a deceased former member of the
44 General Assembly.
45 (b) Resolutions of this nature that do not relate to deceased former members shall
46 be excluded from introduction and consideration by the Senate. Senators shall instead utilize
47 Senatorial Statements to recognize other individuals or events of significance.
48 (c) The Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate may refer
49 any such resolution to a committee or place the resolution on the Senate's calendar for a date
50 certain.
