1 (d) During the Senate's consideration of a resolution relating to a deceased
2 member, the Presiding Officer shall order the Chamber secured by the Sergeant-at-Arms so as to
3 prevent the entry or exit of any person.
4 RULE 40.2. Deadlines on filing for introduction of bills. – (a) All local bills must
5 be submitted to either the Legislative Drafting Division or the Legislative Analysis Division of
6 the Legislative Services Office by 4:00 P.M. on Thursday, February 13, 2025, and must be filed
7 for introduction in the Senate before 4:00 P.M. on Thursday, February 27, 2025.
8 (b) All public bills and resolutions, except those listed in subsection (b1) of this
9 rule, must be submitted to either the Legislative Drafting Division or the Legislative Analysis
10 Division of the Legislative Services Office by 4:00 P.M. on Thursday, February 27, 2025, and
11 must be filed for introduction in the Senate before 4:00 P.M. on Tuesday, March 25, 2025.
12 (b1) The following bills are not subject to subsection (b) of this rule: (i) those
13 providing for action on gubernatorial nominations or appointments, (ii) those providing for action
14 on appointments by the General Assembly pursuant to G.S. 120-121, (iii) those proposing
15 amendments to the North Carolina Constitution, (iv) those containing statutory amendments
16 necessary to implement proposed amendments to the North Carolina Constitution, (v) those
17 establishing districts for Congress or State or local entities, (vi) those addressing election laws,
18 (vii) those ratifying amendments to the United States Constitution, and (viii) those adjourning
19 the General Assembly.
20 (c) A two-thirds vote of the membership of the Senate present and voting shall be
21 required to file for introduction any bill or resolution after the dates established by this rule.
22 (d) Bills that are subject to Rule 42 of these rules and local bills may be filed in
23 any regular session that convenes in an even-numbered year.
24 RULE 41. Crossover bill deadline; exemptions. – (a) In order to be eligible for
25 consideration by the Senate during the 2025 or 2026 Regular Session of the 2025 General
26 Assembly, all House bills other than those described in subsection (b) of this rule must be
27 received and read on the floor of the Senate as a message from the House no later than Thursday,
28 May 8, 2025, provided that a message from the House received by the next legislative day stating
29 that a bill has passed its third reading and is being engrossed shall comply with the requirements
30 of this rule and provided that the House accepts Senate bills ordered engrossed on the next
31 legislative day.
32 (b) The following bills are not subject to subsection (a) of this rule: (i) those
33 required to be referred to the Committee on Finance or the Committee on Appropriations/Base
34 Budget by Rule 42, (ii) those providing for action on gubernatorial nominations or appointments,
35 (iii) those providing for action on appointments by the General Assembly pursuant to
36 G.S. 120-121, (iv) those providing for amendments to the North Carolina Constitution, (v) those
37 containing statutory amendments necessary to implement proposed amendments to the North
38 Carolina Constitution, (vi) those establishing districts for Congress or State or local entities, (vii)
39 those addressing election laws, (viii) those ratifying an amendment or amendments to the
40 Constitution of the United States, and (ix) those adjourning the General Assembly.
41 RULE 41.1. Effect of adjournment resolution. – Rules 40.2 and 41 are subject to
42 and may be modified by a resolution jointly adjourning both chambers to a date certain.
43 RULE 42. Reference of appropriation and finance bills. – (a) All bills introduced
44 in the Senate providing for appropriations from the State, or any subdivision thereof, shall, before
45 being considered by the Senate, be referred to the Committee on Appropriations/Base Budget
46 and bills referred to other committees carrying any such provisions shall be reported to the Senate
47 as being bills to be referred to the Appropriations/Base Budget Committee before proper action
48 may be taken by the Senate.
49 (b) All bills introduced in the Senate providing for bond issues, imposing or
50 raising fees or other revenues payable to the State, its agencies, its licensing boards, or any of its
51 subdivisions, levying taxes, or in any manner affecting the taxing power of the State or any
Page 12 Senate Resolution 1-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 subdivision thereof, shall, before being considered by the Senate, be referred to the Committee
2 on Finance, and bills referred to other committees carrying any such provisions shall be reported
3 to the Senate as being bills to be referred to the Committee on Finance before proper action may
4 be taken by the Senate.
5 (c) This rule shall not apply to bills imposing civil penalties, criminal fines,
6 forfeitures, or penalties for infractions.
7 RULE 42.1. Fiscal notes. – (a) A Chair of the Appropriations/Base Budget
8 Committee, or of the Finance Committee, or of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the
9 Senate, upon the floor of the Senate, may request that a fiscal analysis be made of a bill,
10 resolution, or an amendment to a bill or resolution which is in the possession of the Senate and
11 that a fiscal note be attached to the measure, when in the opinion of that Chair the fiscal effects
12 of that measure are not apparent from the language of the measure. No bill, resolution, or
13 amendment for which a fiscal note has been requested may be considered for passage prior to the
14 fiscal note being attached to it.
15 (b) The fiscal note shall be filed and attached to the bill, resolution, or amendment
16 within two legislative days of the request. If it is impossible to prepare a fiscal note within two
17 legislative days, the Director of Fiscal Research shall, in writing, so advise the Presiding Officer,
18 the Principal Clerk, and the member introducing or proposing the measure and shall indicate the
19 time when the fiscal note will be ready.
20 (c) The fiscal note shall be prepared by the Fiscal Research Division on a form
21 approved by the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate as to content and
22 form and signed by the staff member or members preparing it. If no estimate in dollars is possible,
23 the fiscal note shall indicate the reasons that no estimate is provided. The fiscal note shall not
24 comment on the merit but may identify technical problems. The Fiscal Research Division shall
25 make the fiscal note available to the membership of the Senate.
26 (d) A sponsor of a bill, resolution, or amendment may deliver a copy of that
27 member's bill, resolution, or amendment to the Fiscal Research Division for the preparation of a
28 fiscal note. The sponsor shall attach the fiscal note to the bill when the sponsor files the bill or
29 resolution or to the amendment when the sponsor moves its adoption.
30 (e) The sponsor of a bill, resolution, or amendment to which a fiscal note is
31 attached who objects to the estimates and information provided may reduce to writing the
32 objections. These objections shall be appended to the fiscal note attached to the bill, resolution,
33 or amendment and to the copies of the fiscal note available to the membership.
34 (f) Subsection (a) of this rule shall not apply to the Current Operations
35 Appropriations Bill or the Capital Improvement Appropriations Bill. This rule shall not apply to
36 a bill, resolution, or amendment requiring an actuarial note under these rules.
37 RULE 42.2. Actuarial notes. – If required by State law:
38 (a) Every bill or resolution proposing any change in the law relative to any:
39 (1) State, municipal, or other retirement system funded in whole or in part out of
40 public funds; or
41 (2) Program of hospital, medical, disability, or related benefits provided for
42 teachers and State employees, funded in whole or in part by State funds,
43 shall have attached to it at the time of its consideration by any committee a brief explanatory
44 statement or note that shall include a reliable estimate of the financial and actuarial effect of the
45 proposed change, as provided in G.S. 120-114. The actuarial note shall be attached to the jacket
46 of each proposed bill or resolution that is reported favorably by any committee and shall be
47 clearly designated as an actuarial note. Upon its introduction, a bill or resolution described in
48 subdivision (a)(1) of this rule shall be referred to the Committee on Pensions and Retirement and
49 Aging.
50 (b) The sponsor of the bill or resolution shall present a copy of the measure, with
51 the sponsor's request for an actuarial note, to the Fiscal Research Division, which shall prepare
Senate Resolution 1-First Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the actuarial note as promptly as possible but not later than two weeks after the request is made.
2 Actuarial notes shall be prepared in the order of receipt of request and shall be transmitted to the
3 sponsor of the measure. The actuarial note of the Fiscal Research Division shall be prepared and
4 signed by an actuary.
5 (c) The sponsor of the bill or resolution shall also present a copy of the measure
6 to the chief administrative officer of the system affected by the measure. The chief administrative
7 officer shall have an actuarial note prepared by the system's actuary on the measure and shall
8 transmit the note to the sponsor of the measure not later than two weeks after the request is
9 received. The actuarial note may be attached to the jacket of the measure.
10 (d) The note shall be factual and shall, if possible, provide a reliable estimate of
11 both the immediate effect and, if determinable, the long-range fiscal and actuarial effect of the
12 measure. If, after careful investigation, it is determined that no dollar estimate is possible, the
13 note shall contain a statement to that effect, setting forth the reasons why no dollar estimate can
14 be given. No comment or opinion shall be included in the actuarial note with regard to the merits
15 of the measure for which the note is prepared. Technical and mechanical defects in the measure
16 may be noted.
17 (e) When any committee reports a measure to which an actuarial note is attached
18 at the time of committee consideration, with any amendment of such nature as would
19 substantially affect the cost to or the revenues of any system, the chair of the committee reporting
20 the measure shall obtain from the Fiscal Research Division and the administrator of the affected
21 system an actuarial note of the fiscal and actuarial effect of the proposed amendment. The
22 actuarial note shall be attached to the jacket of the measure. A chair of the Appropriations/Base
23 Budget Committee, or of the Finance Committee, or of the Committee on Rules and Operations
24 of the Senate, upon the floor of the Senate, may request that an actuarial note be attached to a
25 bill, resolution, or an amendment that affects the costs to or the revenues of a system described
26 in this rule and that is in the possession of the Senate, when in the opinion of that chair, the effect
27 to the cost to or the revenues of a system described in this rule are not apparent from the language
28 of the measure. No bill, resolution, or amendment for which an actuarial note has been requested
29 may be considered for passage prior to the actuarial note from both the Fiscal Research Division
30 and the administrator of the affected system being attached to it.
31 (f) The Fiscal Research Division shall make all relevant actuarial notes available
32 to the membership of the Senate.
33 RULE 42.3. Assessment reports. – Municipal Incorporations. Every legislative
34 proposal introduced in the Senate, or received in the Senate from the House, proposing the
35 incorporation of a municipality shall have attached to the jacket of the original bill at the time of
36 its consideration on second or third readings by the Senate or by any committee of the Senate
37 prior to a favorable report, a recommendation from the Municipal Incorporations Subcommittee
38 of the Joint Legislative Committee on Local Government established by Article 20 of Chapter
39 120 of the General Statutes. The recommendation of that Subcommittee shall be made in
40 accordance with the provisions and criteria set forth in Article 20 of Chapter 120 of the General
41 Statutes and shall include the findings required to be made by G.S. 120-166 through
42 G.S. 120-170.
43 RULE 42.3A. Proposed increases in incarceration. – If required by State law:
44 (a) Every bill, amendment, and resolution proposing any change in the law that could
45 cause a net increase in the length of time for which persons are incarcerated or the number of
46 persons incarcerated, whether by increasing penalties for violating existing laws, by
47 criminalizing behavior, or by any other means, shall have attached to it at the time of its
48 consideration by the Senate a fiscal note prepared by the Fiscal Research Division. The fiscal
49 note shall be prepared in consultation with the Sentencing Policy and Advisory Commission and
50 shall identify and estimate, for the first five fiscal years the proposed change would be in effect,
51 all costs of the proposed net increase in incarceration, including capital outlay costs if the
Page 14 Senate Resolution 1-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 legislation would require increased cell space. If, after careful investigation, the Fiscal Research
2 Division determines that no dollar estimate is possible, the note shall contain a statement to that
3 effect, setting forth the reasons why no dollar estimate can be given. No comment or opinion
4 shall be included in the fiscal note with regard to the merits of the measure for which the note is
5 prepared. However, technical and mechanical defects may be noted.
6 (b) The sponsor of each bill, amendment, or resolution to which this subsection
7 applies shall present a copy of the bill, amendment, or resolution with the request for a fiscal note
8 to the Fiscal Research Division. Upon receipt of the request and the copy of the bill, amendment,
9 or resolution, the Fiscal Research Division shall prepare the fiscal note as promptly as possible.
10 The Fiscal Research Division shall prepare the fiscal note and transmit it to the sponsor within
11 two weeks after the request is made, unless the sponsor agrees to an extension of time.
12 (c) This fiscal note shall be attached to the original of each proposed bill,
13 amendment, or resolution that is reported favorably by any committee, but shall be separate from
14 the bill, amendment, or resolution and shall be clearly designated as a fiscal note. A fiscal note
15 attached to a bill, amendment, or resolution pursuant to this subsection is not a part of the bill,
16 amendment, or resolution and is not an expression of legislative intent proposed by the bill,
17 amendment, or resolution.
18 (d) If a committee reports favorably a proposed bill or resolution with an
19 amendment that proposes a change in the law that could cause a net increase in the length of time
20 for which persons are incarcerated or the number of persons incarcerated, whether by increasing
21 penalties for violating existing laws, by criminalizing behavior, or by any other means, the chair
22 of the committee shall obtain from the Fiscal Research Division and attach to the amended bill
23 or resolution a fiscal note as provided in this rule.
24 RULE 42.4. (Reserved for future use).
25 RULE 42.5. Appropriations/Base Budget Committee meetings. – The
26 Appropriations/Base Budget Cochairs may in their exclusive discretion direct that the
27 Appropriations/Base Budget Committee or its subcommittees or both may consider the budget
28 and the budget plan, including all appropriations, in separate meetings from the House of
29 Representatives and may do all things separately from the House of Representatives.
30 RULE 43. First reading; reference to committee. – All bills filed for introduction
31 and all House bills received in the Office of the Principal Clerk not later than one and one-half
32 hours preceding the convening of the Senate, upon presentation to the Senate, shall be read in
33 regular order of business by their number and title, which shall constitute the first reading of the
34 bill. The Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate or, in the Chair's absence,
35 the Vice-Chair of the Committee or the President Pro Tempore may refer to a Senate committee
36 all bills introduced in the Senate or received from the House of Representatives. Upon the referral
37 being made, the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate shall notify the
38 Principal Clerk of the Senate of the referral, and the Reading Clerk shall announce the referral of
39 the bill. The Principal Clerk shall inform the Presiding Officer of the referral. The title and
40 referral shall be entered upon the Journal.
41 Bills may be referred to more than one committee serially: e.g., "S.B. _________ is
42 referred to the Committee on Finance and upon a favorable report referred to the
43 Appropriations/Base Budget Committee."
44 RULE 44. Bills to receive three readings. – Every bill shall receive three readings
45 before being passed, and the Presiding Officer shall give notice at each reading whether it be the
46 first, second, or third. Unless a member of the Senate objects, a bill may be referred to, and
47 presented to the Senate, by its bill number and short title. The Reading Clerk shall announce the
48 referral as set forth in Rule 43. No bill shall be amended upon the floor of the Senate, except
49 under Rule 45.1, until it has been twice read. Senate simple resolutions shall not require three
50 readings.
Senate Resolution 1-First Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 RULE 45. Reports of committees. – Every Senator presenting a report of a
2 committee shall endorse the report with the name of the committee. The report of the committee
3 shall show that a quorum of the committee was present and a majority of those present voted in
4 favor of the report. Every report of the committee upon a bill or resolution shall stand upon the
5 general orders with the bill or resolution. No committee shall report a bill or resolution without
6 prejudice.
7 RULE 45.1. Action on amendment or committee substitute; distribution of
8 committee substitutes. – (a) If any committee recommends adoption of an amendment or
9 committee substitute of a bill or resolution, the amendment or committee substitute shall be
10 considered adopted upon the reading of the committee report. Unless otherwise calendared by
11 the President Pro Tempore or the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate
12 pursuant to Rule 47, the bill or resolution, as amended, or its adopted committee substitute shall
13 be placed on the calendar for the next legislative day or re-referred if the bill or resolution was
14 serially referred. The committee substitute's original bill or resolution shall lie on the table.
15 (b) Notwithstanding any other provision of this rule, a committee substitute for a
16 simple resolution shall be placed on the calendar for the next legislative day for a vote on its
17 adoption.
18 (c) Unless (i) a committee substitute of a bill or resolution being considered by a
19 committee is distributed to members of that committee no later than 6:00 P.M. the day prior to
20 the committee meeting or (ii) prior approval is given by the Chair of the Committee on Rules and
21 Operations of the Senate to take up and vote on the committee substitute at the meeting noticed,
22 the committee substitute shall be carried over to the next day.
23 RULE 46. Unfavorable report by committee. – All bills reported unfavorably by
24 the committee to which they were referred shall lie upon the table but may be taken from the
25 table and placed upon the calendar by a two-thirds vote of the membership of the Senate present
26 and voting.
27 RULE 47. Recall of bill from committee and discharge petition; calendaring,
28 re-calendaring, or referral of a bill to committee. – (a) Notwithstanding anything to the
29 contrary, only the President Pro Tempore, the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations
30 of the Senate, or the chair of a committee to which a bill or other matter is assigned may, with
31 the consent of a majority of the membership of the Senate present and voting, recall the measure
32 from its assigned committee to be referred to another committee or the floor. Only the President
33 Pro Tempore or the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate may, with the
34 consent of a majority present and voting, calendar a bill or resolution, re-calendar a bill or
35 resolution appearing on the calendar, or refer or re-refer it to committee.
36 (b) A motion to discharge a committee from consideration of a bill or resolution
37 may be filed with the Principal Clerk if accompanied by a petition signed by two-thirds of the
38 membership of the Senate asking that the committee be discharged from further consideration of
39 the bill or resolution. No petition may be circulated for signatures until 10 legislative days after
40 the bill has been referred to the committee. No petition may be circulated for signature until
41 notice has been given on the floor of the Senate that the petition is to be circulated. If such a
42 motion accompanied by a valid petition is filed, the Principal Clerk shall place that motion on
43 the calendar for the next legislative day as a special order of business. If the motion is adopted
44 by two-thirds of the membership of the Senate, then the committee to which the bill or resolution
45 has been referred is discharged from further consideration of the bill or resolution, and that bill
46 or resolution is placed on the calendar for the next legislative day as a special order of business.
47 If the committee had, prior to discharge, adopted any amendment or committee substitute for the
48 bill, it shall be in order to offer that amendment or substitute on the floor as if it were a committee
49 amendment or substitute. The Principal Clerk shall provide a form for discharge petitions.
50 (c) This rule shall not be temporarily suspended.
Page 16 Senate Resolution 1-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 RULE 48. Calendar; order to be followed. – The Presiding Officer and the Principal
2 Clerk of the Senate shall see that all bills are acted upon by the Senate in the order in which they
3 stand upon the calendar, unless otherwise ordered in accordance with Rule 47. The published
4 calendar shall include all bills reported favorably from committees, or placed on the calendar on
5 motion, and shall include the bill number and short title of each bill on the calendar.
6 RULE 49. Consideration of gubernatorial nominations or appointments. – When
7 received by the Principal Clerk, written notice of a gubernatorial nomination or appointment that
8 requires confirmation by the General Assembly or the Senate shall be read in session and shall
9 be referred by the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate, or in the Chair's
10 absence the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, to the appropriate Senate committee. The Chair
11 of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate may file an appropriate resolution for
12 consideration of the nomination or appointment. For statewide or at-large nominations or
13 appointments, the Principal Clerk shall transmit a copy of the notice of nomination or
14 appointment to the Senator or Senators representing the county in which the nominee or
15 appointee resides. For nominations or appointments of persons to represent a particular district
16 or region of the State, the Principal Clerk shall transmit a copy of the notice of nomination or
17 appointment to the Senator or Senators representing all or a portion of the particular district or
18 region to be represented. The chair of the Senate committee receiving referral of any nomination
19 or appointment shall determine the procedure by which the committee shall consider that
20 nomination or appointment and may make a report of its recommendation to the Senate.
21 RULE 50. Third reading requirements. – No bill on its third reading shall be acted
22 upon out of the regular order in which it stands on the calendar, and no bill shall be acted upon
23 on its third reading the same day on which it passed its second reading, unless so ordered by
24 three-fifths of the membership of the Senate present and voting.
25 RULE 51. Special orders. – Any bill or other matter in consideration before the
26 Senate may be made a special order for a subsequent day or hour by a vote of the majority of the
27 Senators voting, and if action on the bill is not completed on that day, it shall be returned to its
28 place on the calendar, unless it is made a special order for another day; and when a special order
29 is under consideration it shall take precedence over any special order or subsequent order for the
30 day, but such subsequent order may be taken up immediately after the previous special order has
31 been disposed of.
32 RULE 52. Procedure when necessary number of Senators not present. – If, on
33 taking the question on a bill, it appears that a constitutional quorum is not present, or if the bill
34 requires a vote of a certain proportion of all the Senators to pass it, and it appears that such
35 number is not present, the bill shall be again read and the question taken thereon; if the bill fails
36 a second time for the want of the necessary number being present and voting, the bill shall not
37 be finally lost but shall be returned to the calendar in its proper order.
38 RULE 53. Effect of defeated measure. – (a) After a bill has been tabled, or has failed
39 to pass on any of its readings, the contents of such bill or the principal provisions of its subject
40 matter shall not be embodied in any other measure. After an amendment has been tabled or
41 defeated on the Senate floor, the contents of such amendment or the principal provisions of its
42 subject matter shall not be embodied in any other measure. If a substitute amendment is adopted
43 on the floor, the contents of the previously pending amendment which are not contained in the
44 substitute shall be considered to have been defeated. Upon the point of order being raised and
45 sustained by the Presiding Officer, such measure shall be laid upon the table and shall not be
46 taken therefrom except by a two-thirds vote of the membership of the Senate present and voting:
47 Provided, no local bill shall be held by the Presiding Officer as embodying the provisions of, or
48 being identical with, any statewide measure which has been laid upon the table or failed to pass
49 any of its readings.
