General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) When a bill has been postponed indefinitely by the Senate, the bill shall lie
2 upon the table and shall not be taken therefrom except by a two-thirds vote of the membership
3 of the Senate present and voting.
4 RULE 54. Taking bill from table. – No bill which has been laid upon the table shall
5 be taken therefrom except by a two-thirds vote of the membership of the Senate present and
6 voting.
7 RULE 54.1. Bill title. – The title of each bill shall adequately and fairly reflect its
8 subject matter.
9 RULE 55. Amending titles of bills. – When a bill is materially modified or the scope
10 of its application extended or decreased, or if the county or counties to which it applies is
11 changed, the title of the bill shall be changed by the committee having it in charge or by the
12 Principal Clerk, so as to indicate the full purport of the bill as amended and the county or counties
13 to which it applies.
14 RULE 56. Corrections of typographical errors in bills. – The Enrolling Clerk is
15 authorized to make corrections of typographical errors in the text of bills at any time prior to
16 ratification. Before the correction is made, the Enrolling Clerk shall have the approval of the
17 Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate or, in the Chair's absence, the
18 Vice-Chair of said Committee, the President Pro Tempore, or the Deputy President Pro Tempore.
19 RULE 56.1. Amendments and committee substitutes adopted by the House to
20 bills originating in the Senate. – (a) Whenever the House has adopted an amendment or a
21 committee substitute for a bill originating in the Senate, and has returned the bill to the Senate
22 for concurrence in that amendment or committee substitute, the Senate may not concur in that
23 amendment or committee substitute until the next legislative day following the day on which the
24 Senate receives that measure, unless otherwise calendared by the President Pro Tempore or the
25 Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate pursuant to Rule 47.
26 (b) The Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate, (or in that
27 Chair's absence the President Pro Tempore) may, or upon motion supported by a majority of the
28 membership of the Senate present and voting shall, refer the bill to an appropriate committee for
29 consideration of the amendment or committee substitute.
30 (c) The Presiding Officer shall, in placing the bill on the calendar, rule whether
31 the amendment or committee substitute is a material amendment under Article II, Section 23, of
32 the State's Constitution. If the measure is referred to committee, the committee shall:
33 (1) Report the bill with the recommendation either that the Senate do concur or
34 that the Senate do not concur; and
35 (2) Advise the Presiding Officer as to whether or not the amendment or committee
36 substitute is a material amendment under Article II, Section 23, of the State's
37 Constitution.
38 (d) If the amendment or committee substitute for a bill is not a material
39 amendment, the question before the Senate shall be concurrence. In the event there is more than
40 one House amendment, the question shall be concurrence in all the House amendments, and the
41 question may not be divided, notwithstanding Rule 28. The question that shall be put before the
42 Senate by the Presiding Officer shall be: "Does the Senate concur in the House amendments
43 (committee substitute) to S.B.______?".
44 (e) If the amendment or committee substitute for a bill is a material amendment,
45 the receiving of that bill on messages shall constitute first reading, and the question before the
46 Senate shall be concurrence on second reading. If the motion is passed, the question then shall
47 be concurrence on third reading on the next legislative day.
48 (f) No committee substitute adopted by the House to a bill originating in the
49 Senate may be amended by the Senate.
50 RULE 57. Conference committee. – The President Pro Tempore of the Senate, or in
51 the President Pro Tempore's absence, the Deputy President Pro Tempore, upon motion, may
Page 18 Senate Resolution 1-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 appoint a conference committee when the Senate fails to concur in amendments or committee
2 substitutes put by the House to a bill originating in the Senate, or when the House of
3 Representatives fails to concur in amendments or committee substitutes put by the Senate to a
4 bill originating in the House. Senate conferees shall include the primary sponsor of the bill. In
5 considering the bill committed to the conferees, only such matters as are germane to the bill shall
6 be considered by the conferees, and the conference report shall deal only with such matters. The
7 matters referred to the conference committee by the conference committee chairs shall go to and
8 be considered by the conferees appointed by the Senate and the House of Representatives. While
9 the bill is in conference committee, the Senate's position shall be determined by a majority of the
10 Senate conferees. Upon agreement by the Senate and House of Representatives, a conference
11 report shall be drafted reflecting the matters considered and agreed upon by the conferees. The
12 conference report shall not be amended. A conference report in order under this Rule when
13 reported to the Senate shall be calendared for consideration of the question of adoption on any
14 date specified by the Chair of the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate, or in the
15 absence of the Chair, by the President Pro Tempore. In the absence of any such specification it
16 shall be calendared for the next legislative day.
17 RULE 57.1. Germaneness of amendment or committee substitute. – (a) All floor
18 amendments shall be germane to the subject matter of the measure under consideration. The
19 question of germaneness of the proposed floor amendment is in order at any time the measure is
20 before the body prior to final action on its adoption.
21 (b) In committee, the germaneness of amendments or committee substitutes shall
22 be determined by the chair of the committee in which such amendments or committee substitutes
23 are offered.
24 RULE 58. Certification of passage of bills. – The Principal Clerk shall certify the
25 passage of bills by the Senate, with the date thereof, together with the fact whether passed by
26 vote of three-fifths or two-thirds of the membership of the Senate present and voting, whenever
27 such vote may be required by the Constitution or laws of the State.
28 RULE 59. Transmittal of bills to House. – No bill shall be sent from the Senate on
29 the day of its passage except on the last day of the session, unless otherwise ordered by a majority
30 vote of the membership of the Senate present and voting.
31 RULE 59.1. Engrossment. – Bills which originate in the Senate and that are amended
32 shall be engrossed before being sent to the House.
33 RULE 59.2. Vetoed bills. – (a) Unless directed otherwise by the President Pro
34 Tempore of the Senate on behalf of the Senate, the Principal Clerk or an employee designated by
35 the Principal Clerk shall receive Senate bills not approved by the Governor. The veto message
36 shall be read in the Senate on the next legislative day following its receipt by the Principal Clerk.
37 (b) Upon a veto message's being read in the Senate, the Chair of the Committee
38 on Rules and Operations of the Senate shall either refer the bill and the Governor's objections
39 and veto message to committee or place the bill on the calendar for a day certain. The Chair of
40 the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate or the Chair's designee shall give the Senate
41 Minority Leader at least 24 hours' notice that a vetoed bill may be considered by the Senate.
42 VII. LEGISLATIVE OFFICERS AND EMPLOYEES
43 RULE 60. Pages. – (a) The President Pro Tempore of the Senate shall appoint pages.
44 The President Pro Tempore, or such person as the President Pro Tempore may designate, shall
45 supervise the pages and assign to them their duties. Each page shall be in the tenth, eleventh, or
46 twelfth grade at the time of service.
47 (b) Members may designate honorary pages by a statement delivered to the
48 Principal Clerk who will have a certificate issued therefor.
49 RULE 61. Sergeants-at-Arms. – (a) There shall be 16 positions of Assistant
50 Sergeants-at-Arms, to be appointed upon the recommendation of the President Pro Tempore by
Senate Resolution 1-First Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the Sergeant-at-Arms, who are to work under his or her supervision and to be assigned such
2 duties and powers as he or she shall direct.
3 (b) The Sergeant-at-Arms shall be responsible for the safety of the members and
4 employees of the Senate while in the Senate Chamber or any place in which the Senate or its
5 committees are in session.
6 (c) The Sergeant-at-Arms shall serve all warrants and subpoenas issued by orders
7 of the Senate and signed by the Presiding Officer of the Senate, and said warrants and subpoenas
8 shall be returnable to the Principal Clerk of the Senate.
9 RULE 62. Principal Clerk's staff. – The Principal Clerk of the Senate shall employ
10 all necessary employees and clerks required to carry out the duties of that office. The Principal
11 Clerk shall have supervision and control and shall assign such duties and powers as the Principal
12 Clerk shall direct to the employees and clerks of that office.
13 RULE 63. Legislative assistants and other Senate staff. – (a) Each member shall
14 be assigned one legislative assistant position. Additional staff positions may be allocated to
15 members in the discretion of the President Pro Tempore. The selection of the person to fill a staff
16 position assigned or allocated to an individual member's office shall be his or her prerogative.
17 (b) Persons seeking an employment position in the office of an individual member
18 shall file initial applications for employment with the Director of Legislative Assistants and shall
19 receive compensation as prescribed by the Legislative Services Commission. Their period of
20 employment shall comply with the period as established by the Legislative Services Commission
21 unless employment for an extended period is approved by the President Pro Tempore. They shall
22 adhere to such uniform regulations and other conditions of employment (including retention)
23 under the direction of the Director of Senate Legislative Assistants as the Committee on Rules
24 and Operations of the Senate shall adopt.
25 (c) The Director of Senate Legislative Assistants and any assistants shall be
26 appointed by the President Pro Tempore of the Senate.
27 RULE 64. Senate Journal. – The President Pro Tempore of the Senate shall cause
28 the Journal of the Senate to be examined daily before the hour of convening to determine if the
29 proceedings of the previous day have been correctly recorded.
30 RULE 65. Deputy President Pro Tempore. – The Senate shall elect a Deputy
31 President Pro Tempore. Upon a vacancy in the office of President Pro Tempore, the Senate shall
32 elect one of its members to succeed to that office.
33 VIII. GENERAL RULES
34 RULE 66. President to sign papers. – All addresses and all warrants and subpoenas
35 issued by order of the Senate shall be signed by the President, the President Pro Tempore, or the
36 Deputy President Pro Tempore. All acts and resolutions shall be signed by the President, the
37 President Pro Tempore, the Deputy President Pro Tempore, or by a Senator designated by the
38 President Pro Tempore to act as Presiding Officer.
39 RULE 67. Admission to the floor of the Senate. – No person except members of the
40 Senate, members of the House of Representatives, staff of the General Assembly; staff of the
41 Lieutenant Governor; Judges of the Supreme Court, Court of Appeals, and Superior Courts; the
42 Governor and members of the Council of State; former members of the General Assembly; and
43 persons particularly invited and extended the privileges of the floor by the Presiding Officer shall
44 be admitted to the floor of the Senate either during its session or be admitted to or remain on the
45 floor of the Senate within 15 minutes prior to the Senate's scheduled daily session.
46 Notwithstanding any other provision of these rules, no registered lobbyist shall: (i) be admitted
47 to the floor of the Senate or Senate Chamber while the Senate is in session, (ii) be admitted to or
48 remain on the floor of the Senate within 15 minutes prior to the Senate's scheduled daily session,
49 or (iii) except when a committee is meeting on the floor, be admitted to the floor of the Senate
50 for the 15 minutes after adjournment of the Senate. When the Senate is not in daily session, the
51 President Pro Tempore shall determine the privileges of the floor.
Page 20 Senate Resolution 1-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 RULE 67.1. Recognition for extending courtesies. – (a) Courtesies of the floor and
2 galleries shall be extended only by the Presiding Officer on the Presiding Officer's own motion
3 or upon the written request of a member of the Senate to former members of the General
4 Assembly or to distinguished visitors.
5 (b) The Presiding Officer, upon written request at intervals between various
6 orders of business, may extend courtesies to schools or other special large groups visiting in the
7 galleries while they are present, and the Presiding Officer shall, at such times as deemed
8 appropriate, express to those visitors in the galleries the pleasure of the Senate for their presence.
9 RULE 68. Privileges of the floor. – No group or individual other than members of
10 the Senate may make remarks upon the floor of the Senate.
11 RULE 69. News media. – The President Pro Tempore is authorized to assign area
12 and equipment on the floor of the Senate for the use of the representatives of news media, and
13 the President Pro Tempore shall provide regulations for the operation of the representatives of
14 the news media on the floor of the Senate.
15 RULE 70. Absence without leave. – No Senator or officer of the Senate shall depart
16 the service of the Senate without leave or receive pay as a Senator or officer for the time absent
17 without leave.
18 RULE 71. Circulation of materials. – Any material circulated to Senate members
19 anywhere in the Legislative Building or the Legislative Office Building shall bear the name of
20 the originator. No items may be placed on members' desks in the Senate Chamber except as
21 permitted under Rule 17.
22 RULE 72. Assignment of seats; offices. – (a) The President Pro Tempore of the
23 Senate shall assign seats in the Senate Chamber to the members elected. The President Pro
24 Tempore, when assigning seats, may give preferential consideration to the respective members
25 according to the length of service that each member has rendered in the Senate. No incumbent
26 appointed to fill an unexpired term in the immediate preceding session shall retain the seat if
27 requested by a Senator elected to said session.
28 (b) Not later than two weeks after the initial committee assignments become final,
29 the President Pro Tempore of the Senate is authorized to make assignments of committee rooms
30 and offices to designated committees, chairs, and members of the Senate. In making such
31 assignments of individual offices, the President Pro Tempore may give preferential consideration
32 to the respective members according to the length of service that each member has rendered in
33 the Senate.
34 RULE 73. Administrative rules and regulations involving Senate employees. –
35 All administrative rules, regulations, and orders involving all individuals employed to perform
36 duties for the Senate, other than those appointed by the Principal Clerk and the Sergeant-at-Arms,
37 shall be first approved by the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate.
38 RULE 74. Public hearings. – Any Senator may request in writing a public hearing
39 by the committee considering the bill on a public bill. Requests may be granted at the discretion
40 of the chair. Notice shall be given not less than five calendar days prior to public hearings. Such
41 notices shall be issued as information for the press, and the information shall be posted in the
42 places designated by the Principal Clerk.
43 RULE 75. Public hearings; filing of written statements. – Persons desiring to
44 appear and be heard at a public hearing are encouraged to file with the chair of the committee a
45 brief or a written statement of the remarks to be made at least 24 hours before the time of the
46 hearing.
47 RULE 76. Voting in joint sessions. – When the Senate sits jointly with the House,
48 either in committee or in joint session, the Senate reserves the right to vote separately.
49 RULE 77. Alteration, suspension, or rescission of rules. – (a) These rules may not
50 be permanently rescinded or altered except by Senate simple resolution passed by a three-fifths
51 vote of the membership of the Senate. The introducer of the resolution must, on the floor of the
Senate Resolution 1-First Edition Page 21

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Senate, give notice of the intent to introduce the resolution on the legislative day preceding its
2 introduction.
3 (b) Except as otherwise provided herein, the Senate, upon motion of the Chair of
4 the Committee on Rules and Operations of the Senate, the President Pro Tempore of the Senate,
5 or the Deputy President Pro Tempore of the Senate, and the three-fifths vote of the membership
6 of the Senate present and voting, may temporarily suspend any of these rules.
7 SECTION 2. This resolution is effective upon adoption.
